Composer JoAnn Kuchera-Morin works on  the Allosphere, one of the largest scientific and artistic instruments in the world. Based at UCSB, the Allosphere and its 3D immersive theater maps complex data in time and space. Kuchera-Morin founded the Center for Research in Electronic Art Technology (CREATE) and has been the director since its birth in 1986. In 2000 she began work on a Digital Media Center within the California NanoSystems Institute at Santa Barbara. Her fascinations include gestural interfaces for performance and the expression of complex data in nontraditional forms.

Hew own music explores the boundaries of electric/acoustic instrumentation, welcoming digital players into the ensemble in works such as Concerto For Clarinet and Clarinets, a composition for solo clarinet and computer-generated tape.

title: Stunning data visualization in the AlloSphere

aws-transcripts.transcript: Theo Alice Fear. It's a three storey metal sphere in an echo free chamber. Think of the Alice Fear is a large, dynamically varying digital microscope that's connected to a supercomputer. 20 researchers can stand on a bridge suspended inside of the sphere and be completely immersed in their data. Imagine if a team of physicists could stand inside of an Adam and watch and hear electron spin. Imagine if a group of sculptors could be inside of lattice of atoms and sculpt with their material. Imagine if a team of surgeons could fly into the brain as though it was a world, and see tissues is landscapes and hear blood density levels is music. This is some of the research that you're going to see that we're undertaking at the Alice Fear, but first, a little bit about this group of artists, scientists and engineers that are working together. I'm a composer orchestra Lee trained in the inventor of the Alice Fear. With my visual artist colleagues, we map complex mathematical algorithms that unfold in time and space, visually and sonically. Our scientists colleagues are finding new patterns in the information, and our engineering colleagues were making one of the largest dynamically varying computers in the world. For this kind of data exploration, I'm going to fly you into five research projects in the Alice Fear that they're going to take you from biological macroscopic data all the way down to electron spin.
